<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-010-322 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 500 750</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 18 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC publicly opens operating systems. (company plans to licenseVMS)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miyazawa, Masayuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (Licenses).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Product:   VMS (Operating system) (Licenses).andO;Topic:     LicensingStrategic PlanningThird-Party VendorsOperating systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****DEC Publicly Opens Operating Systems 11/18/91 TOKYO, JAPAN, 1991 NOV 18(NB) -- A reports says that Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) will open itsVAX operating system architecture to third parties.andP;  DEC's Vice PresidentWilliam Johnson told the Nikkan Kogyo newspaper that DEC group will licensethis proprietary information to third party computer and software makers.andM;DEC is expected to license its latest version of the VMS operating system tocomputer makers next year.andP;  This VMS will run on a next-generation VAXmachine, which is based on the RISC (reduced instruction set computing) chip.andO;The next generation VAX, currently being developed, is expected to be on themarket by the end of next year.andP;  It will be extremely powerful, equipped witha 64-bit 200MHz RISC chip which operates almost twice as fast as the currentRISC chip.andP;  This VAX machine will be compatible with the current VAX familyat source level.andM;William Johnson was quoted by the Nikkan Kogyo as saying that DEC willcontinue to market both its RISC-chip based VAX family and its CISC (commandinstruction set computing)-chip based VAX family in the next five to sevenyears.andP;  Then, DEC will sell only its RISC chip-based VAX family.andM;DEC's strategy is to encourage hardware makers to produce and sellVAX-compatible computers.andP;  This will stimulate software makers to producemore quality programs for the VAX family.andP;  It is similar to IBM Japan'sstrategy.andP;  IBM Japan has been licensing its large- scale computers operatingsystems to Fujitsu and Hitachi.andP;  In this way, IBM's machines dominate amongbusiness users in Japan.andM;(Masayuki Miyazawa/19911118/Press Contact: IBM Japan, andplus;81-3-3586- 1111)</TEXT></DOC>